<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-162-910  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 162 910.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  April 3 1989 v23 n14 p101(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Hacker stereotypes changing.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Alexander, Michael.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Computer hackers have broken out of their old stereotypes.andP;  Theinformation necessary to commit computer crime is spreadingrapidly through the population as computers are becoming easier toaccess.andP;  According to a recent report published by the NationalCenter for Computer Crime Data (NCCCD), 32 percent of the peoplearrested for computer crimes are women, 43 percent are minoritiesand 67 percent are between the ages of 21 and 35.andP;  Former andcurrent employees are far more likely to breach a company'scomputer than someone from outside the company.andP;  Seventy percentof all computer crimes involve the theft of money or services.andO;The NCCCD estimates that computer crimes cost the US $555 millionin 1988.andP;  Also, 15 computer-years were lost in down time and 930man-years were spent detecting and removing viruses.andP;  The arrestof computer criminals and the laws concerning them are examined.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     National Center for Computer Crime DataLaw enforcementComputer CrimeReportsUser Behavior.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotographgraph.andO;Caption:   An analysis of computer crime prosecutions. (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>